xt of a widespread American concern with the mental health of its citizens. Mendes shows the clinic to have been simultaneously a scientific and political gambit, challenging both a racist mental health care system and supposedly color-blind psychiatrists who failed to consider the consequences of oppression in their assessment and treatment of African American patients. Employing the methods of oral history, archival research, textual analysis, and critical race philosophy, Under the Strain of Color contributes to a growing body of scholarship that highlights the interlocking relationships among biomedicine, institutional racism, structural violence, and community health activism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxMental health servicesxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aAfrican AmericansxMental health serviceszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aAfrican AmericansxMental healthxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aAfrican AmericansxMental healthzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aCommunity psychiatryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aCommunity psychiatryzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aSocial psychiatryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aSocial psychiatryzNew York (State)zNew York. 4aAfrican-American Studies. 4aPsychology & Psychiatry. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / African American .2bisacsh  aBrown v. Board of Education and social science, healthcare and civil rights, black mental health, Richard Wright.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170139940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501701399423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501701399/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL 